Just about a year ago, I happened to watch some new people train their dogs. I remember I was so impressed. Their sessions started with intention - there was a warm up routine (something completely foreign to me at that point). Then the entire session just flowed effortlessly between obedience and play. There was no awkward down time or disengagement between the handler and the dog. The dogs looked so happy to be working and the handlers were clear and focused in their communication. I remember thinking, wow, how do we get on that level ü§©

Fast forward to 2024 and it feels like we are finally making some moves! There‚Äôs still a ton of work to do, but I‚Äôve been so grateful to learn from some super talented teams these past few months. Hello from the girlies! They have been loving the extra space at our new place, but now that we live in a 2-story house, I‚Äôve incorporated some changes to minimize risk of joint issues and osteoarthritis, especially since these two are getting up there in age (nearly 10 and 11 ü•∫)

‚òëÔ∏è Block off stairs to prevent excessive stress on the joints
‚òëÔ∏è Add joint supporting supplements to their daily meals
‚òëÔ∏è Cover highly trafficked areas in the home with rugs to reduce slipping
‚òëÔ∏è Reduce calories to account for slower metabolisms

What a year for Kibo! 

We kicked off 2023 by showing in Best In Show and securing his spot as the #4 White Shepherd in the USA. My goal this year was to switch focus from conformation to sports, and we ended up picking up some NACSW nosework titles and passing his IGP BH-VT! The year was not only filled with early mornings, long drives, and training sessions, but also so many good times spent with friends both new and old, laughing, playing, hiking, eating, gaming, shopping, swimming‚Ä¶ all with Kibo by my side. 

In just a few days he will be 3 years old and we‚Äôll embark on yet another year of fun together. Onwards and upwards to 2024!
